Project Outcomes 2018

The GLOBE (Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment) Program is an international science education program that connects students, teachers, scientists and citizen scientists in creating a deeper understanding of local and global environments through data collection and analysis. Each year GLOBE holds a meeting where the community comes together to learn about new developments and also present their GLOBE results. In 2017, the annual meeting was held at Southern Connecticut State University, in New Haven CT, from July 30-August 3.   

In total, 243 participants attended the meeting from 38 countries, with 131 participants from the US. The US delegation included 39 partners, 6 trainers, 11 teachers, 10 students, exhibitors, and federal sponsors.

GLOBE students came together to present their research and also had a separate field experience from the adult participants. Twenty-two student research posters were presented at this meeting. The number of research projects per region is displayed below.





