At the end of the week, students presented the results of their field experience to the whole group. Participants asked the students questions on the learning experience and the results they have found from using GLOBE protocols to take earth science measurements.  

While the students were involved in their experience, the adult participants had numerous presentations over the course of four days that covered myriad of topics including:

Coastal Measurements; 
The Importance of Ongoing Environmental Monitoring; 
The Value of Citizen Science and GLOBE; 
How Local GLOBE Students can Connect their Data Collection to the Needs of Local Community;
GLOBE and Citizen Science;
Creative Models for Implementing GLOBE (at the country level); 
Regional GLOBE Learning Expeditions;
Implementing GLOBE in Your Classroom (International);
Implementing GLOBE in a University;
GLOBE Observer Mosquito Habitat Mapper: Partnerships, Programs and Potential;
Implementing GLOBE in a Classroom (U.S.);
Inclusion in the GLOBE Community-STEM Equity; 
Present and Future Collaborations (considered collaborations that would create additional inclusion from other communities around the world into the program); and  
GLOBE field sessions which included demonstrations on how to use the GLOBE Apps for data entry.


Participants also were engaged in a process around the 2018-2023 Strategic Plan.

At the end of the meeting, the location of the next annual meeting and the GLOBE Learning Expedition, a gathering that occurs every four years, was announced. 

